 GENERAL DESCRIPTION                                               528 1451
   This evaluation is a synthesis of experimental results and      528 1451
 theoretical calculations using the GNASH Hauser-Feshbach,         528 1451
 statistical theory code [ar88, yo77]. It replaces a pre-1970 U.K. 528 1451
 evaluation that was adapted for ENDF/B in 1971 [co79].            528 1451
   Major emphasis was placed on experimental data where possible,  528 1451
 usually using the calculations to estimate shapes and             528 1451
 experimental data to normalize the the calculations. Spherical    528 1451
 optical model calculations were used to obtain particle           528 1451
 transmission coefficients, using global potentials for protons    528 1451
 and alphas, and the work of Dave et al. [Da83] for the neutron    528 1451
 potential.  Gilbert-Cameron level density parameters were used    528 1451
 and preequilibrium corrections from an exciton model were         528 1451
 included. In general, the calculations were required for the      528 1451
 gamma and particle emission spectra from charged-particle         528 1451
 reactions, as well as for inelastic neutron and gamma emission    528 1451
 above the third excited state of B11, and for all states above    528 1451
 an incident neutron energy of about 8 MeV.                        528 1451
